The endangered giant panda population in China has increased to around 1,590, with a rise from 1,100 in the 1980s.
A blood bank at the panda breeding lab will aid in genetic diversity and breeding efforts.
Researchers aim to study panda blood types and DNA for conservation purposes.
The Qinling pandas face a more urgent need for protection due to their smaller numbers.
Giant pandas in Gansu Province are at risk due to blooming bamboo threatening their food source.
Efforts are underway to relocate pandas to areas with better food supply to prevent starvation.
